A Unique Future
JERUSALEM – With my now almost 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone.
Experts examined the past, but due to their entrapment in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, in which, in view of a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, more events are dependent on one another, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation that cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is declining. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are boundless.
Global acting companies want to follow their businesses all over the world, thereby causing on the one hand a loss of sovereignty, but on the other hand weakening racism and prejudices as well as, to a significant extent, nationalism.
Due to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically skilled than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many state leaders and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently governed is unsuitable for the new era.
Yet there are political "free-riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. However, not through the development of a freedom agenda, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, mainly Islamist extremists appropriate the protests of the younger generation for themselves and thereby steal the revolution from them.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the younger generation, can and should not, however, interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are in the heart of the rebellious youth and their legitimate yearning for freedom and fundamental rights, which are supposed to enable them to be heard, to choose their political leadership, and to provide for their livelihood.
Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
Yet there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists are trying to gain control over less well-organized liberals in elections, thereby preventing peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success is based on the fact that the country started with absolutely nothing.
When we returned to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could rely solely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. For this reason, we currently have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and yet achieve higher crop yields per square meter of arable land than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can create a region of hope, development, and success.
Foremost, we must do everything within our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing extremists who seek to manipulate citizen movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral corruption, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. They crush legitimate protests of their own citizens and work against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Furthermore, Iran employs multiple proxies to incite terror against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon, and in Iraq.
If Iran acquires nuclear weapons, the leaders of the country could shake the Near and Middle East and incite even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself when Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
Yet it is not only Israel that is threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability around the world.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is no longer possible.
Beyond these immediate challenges, we all have a duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
To a time when the past has become irrelevant for forecasting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to fully realize their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-expression is just as important as free speech.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back has no meaning.
